    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. it feels like there are a lot of ways they can trap me with the wording if they really wanted to. are there any other subtle things in these types of contracts that people usually miss? like things that aren't super obvious at first glance but end up being a huge problem later?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Another subtle thing to watch out for is \"no-warranty\" or \"no-representation\" clauses. These clauses can essentially disclaim any responsibility for the accuracy or completeness of the information you receive, which can be a huge problem if you rely on that information and it turns out to be incorrect.\n\nFor example, a clause like \"The Disclosing Party makes no representations or warranties, express or implied, regarding the accuracy, completeness, or reliability of the confidential information\" can be very problematic. It's not just about the confidentiality of the information, but also about the accuracy and reliability of that information.\n\nAdditionally, be careful of \"all-encompassing\" language, such as \"any and all\" or \"including without limitation.\" These phrases can be used to cover a wide range of scenarios and can make the contract seem more comprehensive than it actually is.\n\nIt's also worth noting that some contracts may have \"severability\" clauses, which allow the parties to \"sever\" or \"split\" specific clauses if they're held to be invalid. This can essentially render entire sections of the contract null and void if one clause is challenged.",
      "source": "target",
